hands_on_practices.problem:
A team of bioengineers is designing a minimal synthetic organism. To optimize translational efficiency and reduce the genomic cost of encoding transfer RNA (tRNA) genes, they aim to use the minimum number of tRNA species required to decode all codons for a particular amino acid.

The amino acid in question is glycine, which is encoded by the four messenger RNA (mRNA) codons: 5'-GGU-3', 5'-GGC-3', 5'-GGA-3', and 5'-GGG-3'. Your task is to identify a minimal set of two tRNA anticodons that can collectively recognize all four of these glycine codons.

Assume the anticodons can only be constructed using the four canonical ribonucleotides: Adenine (A), Uracil (U), Guanine (G), and Cytosine (C). The pairing rules between the third base of the codon (at the 3' end) and the first base of the anticodon (at the 5' end, also known as the 'wobble' position) are as follows:
- An anticodon base G can pair with codon bases U or C.
- An anticodon base C can pair with codon base G.
- An anticodon base A can pair with codon base U.
- An anticodon base U can pair with codon bases A or G.

Standard Watson-Crick pairing (G with C, A with U) occurs at the other two positions.

Which of the following pairs of anticodon sequences, written 5'-to-3', represents a valid minimal set capable of decoding all four glycine codons?

A. { 5'-UCC-3', 5'-CCC-3' }

B. { 5'-GCC-3', 5'-UCC-3' }

C. { 5'-ACC-3', 5'-GCC-3' }

D. { 5'-CCC-3', 5'-ACC-3' }

E. { 5'-GAA-3', 5'-UAA-3' }
